@garethaustin3137 You can keep your faux shock, thank you very much. The fact is, if you are going to justify terror attacks against civilians or the theft of innocent people's money, on the grounds that apartheid was considered bad enough by Mandela to justify doing this, then you can also justify apartheid on the grounds that the National Party considered apartheid the acceptable alternative to black and communist rule. After all, if you are going to base your argument on what one group considers acceptable, then it raises the question of why what they subjectively consider acceptable is  fine, but not what the opposing side considers acceptable. If the murder of civilians is justifiable because it was in the name of the anti-apartheid struggle, then why is the murder of civilians not fine if it was in the name of preventing black rule, or the spread of communism?
If it comes down to subjective acceptability, then why would terrorism against the South African state be more acceptable than unfair laws? Why would terrorism be fine, but not the arrest of the terrorists? Surely if we are going to say "Well, you can't blame Mandela under the circumstances" and say that people should see it from his point of view, you should also be prepared to see things from the point of view of the South African authorities? You can only get around such a problem in your position if you can claim that one set of views is closer to an objectively better moral position. Can you do this?
It sounds like you have a rather inaccurate view of what apartheid South Africa was like, and comparing it to Nazism is actually a very, very inaccurate thing to do.

